  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone can disrupt cell membranes primarily due to its chemical properties. Here are the main reasons why acetone has this effect:\n\n1. **Polarity and Solubility**: Acetone is a polar solvent, which means it can interact with both polar and nonpolar substances. Cell membranes are primarily composed of phospholipid bilayers, which have hydrophobic (nonpolar) tails and hydrophilic (polar) heads. Acetone can integrate into the lipid bilayer, disrupting the organization and integrity of the membrane.\n\n2. **Disruption of Lipid Interactions**: The incorporation of acetone into the lipid bilayer can interfere with the interactions between the lipid molecules. This can lead to increased fluidity of the membrane, making it more permeable and less stable. When the membrane structure is compromised, it can result in leakage of cellular contents and loss of membrane integrity.\n\n3. **Denaturation of Proteins**: Acetone can also denature proteins, including membrane proteins. This denaturation can affect the function of membrane channels and receptors, further compromising the cell's ability to maintain homeostasis and communicate with its environment.\n\n4. **Solvent Action**: As a solvent, acetone can dissolve lipids and other membrane components. This solvent action can lead to the extraction of lipids from the membrane, further disrupting its structure and function.\n\nOverall, acetone's ability to interact with and disrupt the lipid bilayer and proteins within cell membranes makes it an effective agent for breaking down cell membranes. This property is utilized in various laboratory settings, such as in cell lysis procedures for extracting cellular components.",
